s are associated with similar brain states. The frequency bands that are typically reported on are shown in Table 1, including the brain state they associate with as well as sample EEGs:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/epLsO.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/epLsO.png\" alt=\"![eeg bands\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Table 1. Typical analyzed EEG frequency bands. Source: <a href=\"https://conorrussomanno.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/2.png\" rel=\"nofollow\">Conorrus Somanno<\/a><\/sup>       <\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>Reference<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"https://www.google.com/patents/EP2681729A1?cl=en\" rel=\"nofollow\">Nelson Garcia <em>et al<\/em>. Device and method for cognitive enhancement of a user (2014). Patent <em>EP 2681729 A1<\/em><\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":43514,"question_id":43508,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1455999955}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43508/what-are-wave-frequencies-in-the-eeg","last_activity_date":1456004022,"creation_date":1455966376,"answer_count":1,"title":"What are wave frequencies in the EEG?","body":"<p>Here is a typical EEG reading:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://frontalcortex.com/gallery/pics/33862d0bb418be1a46a7d79f0ae18d32.jpg\" alt=\"EEG\"><\/p>\n\n<p>I understand that each row corresponds to the signal read between two sensors on a standard 10-20 (or 10-5) distribution setup (e.g. <code>C3-P3<\/code>).<\/p>\n\n<p>What I'm missing here is: <strong>what waves are we actually seeing here - alpha, beta, etc.?<\/strong> Or do EEGs not really contain wave types, and instead just show voltage differentials between sensors?<\/p>\n","question_id":43508,"tags":["biophysics","electrophysiology","methods","electroencephalography","signal-processing"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":43514,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":95,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1456004022},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/wtOkm.jpg?s=128&g=1","use