S.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9554,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9554/obsidian-phoenix","reputation":116,"display_name":"Obsidian Phoenix"},"closed_date":1456201589,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"post_id":43474,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455836594,"comment_id":75273,"body":"Given the right set of molecular machinery, neurons can start firing spontaneously. No kickstart needed."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef10e56567f5d6e20bc3f7f4ab4e3254?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":87,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/87/gaurav","reputation":683,"display_name":"Gaurav"},"score":1,"post_id":43474,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455915766,"comment_id":75316,"body":"If nothing else, touch, temperature and other sensory neurons will start firing in response to stimuli detected by the embryo, which will start firing impulses into the brain."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43474/how-is-the-brain-kickstarted-during-development","last_activity_date":1455833054,"creation_date":1455833054,"answer_count":0,"title":"How is the brain kickstarted during development","body":"<p>The brain is a complicated beast, that operates (generally) by electrical activity. During development, all cells originate from the a single \"cell\": the zygote.<\/p>\n\n<p>At some point during development, the cells will begin to form into the specialised cells of the brain. But how does the brain activity start?<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there some process that gets things going, akin to jump starting a car? Specifically, I'm referring to the mammalian (and more specifically human) brain.<\/p>\n","question_id":43474,"tags":["brain","development","mammals"],"scor