th.com/pueschel.htm\">mental deficits<\/a> caused by Down's syndrome:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The majority of children with Down syndrome function in the mild to moderate range of mental retardation. However, some children are not mentally retarded at all; they may function in the borderline to low average range; others may be severely mentally retarded.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>What is the source of the variability in the neurological deficits?<\/strong> For the sake of answerability it may be best to narrow the scope down to the larger chunk of Down's syndrome sufferers with a full trisomy. Does any, or all of the variability in neurological deficits has to do with the stochastic process of <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/x-chromosome-x-inactivation-323\">X-inactivation<\/a>?    <\/p>\n","question_id":43463,"tags":["neuroscience","pathology","human-genetics","neurology"],"score":7,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":68,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1455806719},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/--g2BbRN2DG8/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAEU/TV7HA04D2uE/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":17230,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17230/rishab-bairagi","reputation":593,"display_name":"rishab bairagi","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1455785978,"creation_date":1455785155,"body":"<p><strong>Complete <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_linkage\">genetic linkage<\/a> does occur in some cases.<\/strong> <\/p>\n\n<p>Most of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Y_chromosome\">Y chromosome<\/a> (present as a single copy in males of many species) <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Y_chromosome#Recombination_inhibition\">does not recombine with the X chromosome<\/a>. Any genes in this non-recombining region, <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v423/n6942/full/nature01722.html\">the \"male specific Y\" (which is 95% of the Y)<\/a>, will be \"completely linked\", in other words, they cannot be broken apart by recombination and are inherited as a single unit.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/VnRdql.jpg\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/VnRdql.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Non-recombining region of the Y marked as NRY from <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC79676/\">this paper<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The closer two genes are, the higher the general tendency for them to be co-inherited. When co-inheritance is non-random the genes are in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linkage_disequilibrium\">linkage disequilibrium<\/a>. The <a href=\"http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/pigeons/geneticlinkage/\">genetic linkage<\/a> between genes is measured in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centimorgan\">centimorgans<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm not aware of any completely linked genes in recombining parts of the genome. By definition there is some distance between two linked genes (otherwise it's one pleiotropic gene). Therefore, if recombination is possible, then it is possible for them to become unlinked at some frequency, even if that frequency is extremely small (I could be wrong though, but scholar searches have given me nothing). There are, however, cases of very <em>tight<\/em> linkage between genes (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23602480\">1<\/a>, <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/2364258?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents\">2<\/a>, <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1801321/\">3<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p>Note that <a href=\"https://books.google.se/books?id=plqENXLNAN0C&amp;pg=PA285&amp;lpg=PA285&amp;dq=tight%20genetic%20linkage&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=xyIg0NCNQt&amp;sig=csvzpgjYJMduxETuJ-fVwGpJqQ4&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=0ahUKEwjhsI679oDLAhXBnXIKHZYTDwY4ChDoAQgkMAM#v=onepage&amp;q=tight%20genetic%20linkage&amp;f=false\">factors other than genetic linkage<\/a> can affect linkage disequilibrium.<\/p>\n","answer_id":43462,"question_id":43460,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1455785978}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43460/is-complete-genetic-linkage-possible","last_activity_date":1455804569,"creation_date":1455783723,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is complete genetic linkage possible?","body":"<p>Linkage is the tendency of genes on the same chromosome to remain together during the process of inheritance. Is it possible that two genes will remain linked generation after generation without any crossing over between them? Can anyone give an example?<\/p>\n","question_id":43460,"tags":["genetics","genetic-linkage"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":43462,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":53,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1455804569},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a5b21c2db65bfdd434d13368d145709?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":21681,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21681/christy","reputation":16,"display_name":"Christy"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fa7f3890596ea15dcb499602b5e1aa34?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21218,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21218/thawn","reputation":421,"display_name":"Thawn"},"score":2,"post_id":43032,"edited":false,"creation_date":1454672599,"comment_id":74220,"body":"This is a homework question. Unless you show that you made an effort to solve the question yourself it is likely to be closed. <a href=\"http://meta.biology.stackexchange.com/questions/266/homework-policy-for-faq\">Please look here<\/a> on how to properly ask homewor