."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":1,"post_id":43438,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455741760,"comment_id":75229,"body":"I think there is a difference between rational and irrational fear. Irrational fear is not advantageous; rational fear is. A fear of heights is rational; a phobia is not. A phobia is something that actively disrupts someone&#39;s life."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":0,"post_id":43438,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455747247,"comment_id":75233,"body":"@anongoodnurse: Why is a fear of heights (or of anything) advantageous?  As opposed to sensible caution, of course.  From what I&#39;ve seen, it actually makes injury more likely, as the phobic person either freezes, or runs in panic."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe9d73857dd62fae8a55e9430c55a75f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19507,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19507/aleksandrh","reputation":422,"display_name":"AleksandrH","accept_rate":89},"score":0,"post_id":43438,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455751874,"comment_id":75236,"body":"Okay, so I see the distinction now, sorry that I was unable to answer that in my post. @jamesqf Per the definitions we are using, &quot;rational fear&quot; would certainly be advantageous if it leads to avoidance of the risky/dangerous/fear-inducing situation to begin with. So as I pointed out in my fear of heights example (which imo is a rational fear), the person would avoid precarious and elevated scenarios altogether. Granted, this may be a disadvantage if the person needs (for some reason) to be in such a location. For most of the part, though, it would prove advantageous."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1455732947,"creation_date":1455732947,"body":"<p>I think the fault in your reasoning is the assumption that phobias are not advantageous to us. As an example of a potentially useful phobia, consider the fear of heights. Now consider two different ancestors: one who was afraid of heights and one who was not. Generally speaking, the ancestor who was afraid of heights would likely avoid such environments and thereby reduce the likelihood of, say, falling off a cliff or high precipice. In evolutionary terms, we would say that natural selection confers an advantage to the phobia-possessing individual(s). <a href=\"http://serendip.brynmawr.edu/bb/neuro/neuro02/web3/mwhite.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">This<\/a> website in particular has some interesting reading:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Others believe that phobias exist because of evolutionary development to avoid danger in order to improve survival. There are several stimuli that are shared by the most phobic people (heights, insects, crowds, etc.) These phobias, with a couple of exceptions, relate more closely to pre-technological societies. Thus, some scientists, such as Martin Seligman, believe that people are inherently \"prepared\" to fear certain objects. ((5))) In other words, our phobias relate closely to the perils of our ancestors, as through natural selection, those who feared the dangerous stimulus survived while those who didn't, died off. Prepared fears appear to be very easily conditioned. Some scientists, such as LeDoux, believe that preparedness and the ease of conditioning are the result of certain preexisting neurological connections that exist evolutionarily. These connections are turned on with relative ease. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":43438,"question_id":43436,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43436/why-do-phobia-exist-if-they-arent-advantageous","last_activity_date":1455732947,"creation_date":1455729335,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do Phobia exist if they aren't advantageous?","body":"<p>A phobia is usually the irrational fear of something, and the individual experiencing it is often unable to justify whether there is such detestation of something which might not even be threatening. <\/p>\n\n<p>I am aware that there are:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><em>Agoraphobia<\/em><\/li>\n<li><em>Social Phobia<\/em><\/li>\n<li><em>Specific Phobias<\/em> such as <em>Arachnophobia<\/em> (fear of spiders) or <em>Ophidiophobia<\/em> (fear of snakes)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p><strong>My question<\/strong> <strong>is<\/strong>, <em>why do some people have e.g. Arachnophobia but not something closely related such as Entomophobia (fear of insects)? \nAnd why do phobias even exist at all? To me they don't seem to serve a purpose (protection), and do not seem to be of advantageous existence.\nFurthermore, I am curious to why exactly a phobia exists \u2013 and in some cases manages to be  passed on from the parent to the offspring.<\/em> <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>DISCLAIMER:<\/strong> <\/p>\n\n<p>I am aware of there being several psychological processes involved in this such as events that occurred in early years, or if there is a relative with anxiety, the risk of you suffering of a phobia is significantly larger. I also heard there is a high incidence of people developing phobias after traumatic brain injuries. <\/p>\n\n<p>However, I am interested in the biological aspect of a phobia, and that why if it isn't advantageous to us, why does it exist? <\/p>\n","question_id":43436,"tags":["entomology","arachnology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":79,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1455730491},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c844f751084d37da9570bd4d3463d1a8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6037,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6037/mrwonderful","reputation":13,"display_name":"MrWonderful"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":15712,"edited":false,"creation_date":1394779112,"comment_id":21168,"body":"depends on the species and its constitution... Can you be a little more precise.."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/100002639029489/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":5859,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5859/louie-mcconnell","reputation":176,"display_name":"louie mcconnell"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1394806240,"creation_date":1394767932,"body":"<p>Viruses really take to heart the idea of \"quantity, not quality.\" Like animals and plants, viruses and bacteria are a <strong>Completely<\/strong> different ball game (even more so than animals and plants). <\/p>\n\n<p>As you maybe know, you have bacteria floating around you in the air right now. Realistically, a single T4 bacteriophage (a type of virus) has a life cycle of about 20-30 minutes at 37 &deg;C. However, in this time period, it often reproduces in a bacterium and creates tens if not hundreds more phage particles using the bacterium like a machine that was hacked to do its bidding. <\/p>\n\n<p>The only way to prevent a virus from attacking is through vaccinations and other preemptive measures, as it is so difficult to prevent reproduction.<\/p>\n\n<p>Bacteria are so different they, for all intensive purposes, cannot be approximated. For a <strong>rough<\/strong> approximation, somewhere from hours to weeks.<\/p>\n","answer_id":15714,"question_id":15712,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1394806240},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53c30bc1f1ac4e6b256e52b62124da86?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1757,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1757/androidpenguin","reputation":4652,"display_name":"AndroidPenguin","accept_rate":25},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1394806147,"creation_date":1394796297,"body":"<p>It depends entirely on the environment the virus or bacterium is in and also the size of it. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Virus<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>With regards to viruses, the most important thing is typically whether or not the virus has an outer membrane or envelope.<\/p>\n\n<p>Non-enveloped viruses such as rhinoviruses, noroviruses and adenoviruses can in fact survive for long periods outside the host (up to several days) whereas viruses with membranes such as HIV, influenza and the herpes viruses which do well in the host survive for shorter time periods.<\/p>\n\n<p>Experiments with rhinoviruses and influenza viruses have shown potential survival times ranging from a few minutes to 48 hours or more.  They remain active longer on stainless steel, plastic and similar hard surfaces than on fabric and other soft surfaces. <\/p>\n\n<p>This is because many enveloped viruses rely on the proteins on the surface of the membrane to attach to the host cell, this envelope is generally sensitive to degradation to sunlight and normal cleaning procedures.<\/p>\n\n<p>Outbreaks associated with the non-enveloped viruses can continue for many months due to their relative stability in the environment, think of winter vomiting outbreaks, hand foot and mouth in animals as good examples of this phenomenon. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Bacteria<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Because bacteria can undergo metabolism, synthesise proteins etc. for themselves, their life span is usually longer. If we split them into gram positive and gram negative its easier to discuss. Gram positive bacteria have a protein coat that prevents drying allowing them to survive longer. An example is the bacteria Staphylococcus aureus, which is responsible for toxic shock syndrome, food poisoning, and wound infections. With its protein coat it can withstand temperature and humidity extremes. The spore may survive for weeks on dry clothing using sloughed skin cells for food. The Bacillus anthracis, the anthrax bacteria, can also form spores and survive tens to hundreds of years. This is in comparison to gram negative which need humidity. An infamous example is Escherichia coli which survives typically only a few hours at best. <\/p>\n","answer_id":15717,"question_id":15712,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1394806147},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/534e3bd6fc9d8168f4dc8420f7872440?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6054,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6054/inesophet","reputation":46,"display_name":"Inesophet"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1394941999,"creation_date":1394941999,"body":"<p>Virus particles (virions) are not alive. They are just a Genome Delivery Vehicle. They are essentially like landmines. However like different types of landmines different types of viruses can remain \"active\" for longer or shorter.<\/p>\n\n<p>Those depend as explained above on the virion structure but also on Humidity and temperature, the fomite (surface) and the ammount of virions. Some viruses need up to 10k Virons to cause disease. The higher this \"Particle to PFU ratio\" is the lower the chance they can remain active outside the body for long. So if the Virus in question needs few particles, is not enveloped then this one can in theory live for quite a while outside, Norovirus for example is one of those.<\/p>\n","answer_id":15753,"question_id":15712,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/15712/how-do-viruses-or-bacteria-survive-outside-the-body-long-enough-to-spread","last_activity_date":1455732010,"creation_date":1394764984,"answer_count":3,"title":"How do viruses or bacteria survive outside the body long enough to spread?","body":"<p>Say I cough on my table, then someone else touches it and picks up something I've got... how is it that these things can live outside the body, how long can they manage it, and how long is generally 'safe' to consider something no longer carrying these germs?<\/p>\n","question_id":15712,"tags":["bacteriology","pathology","virus"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":15717,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3408,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1455732010},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0la1I.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4833,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4833/dexter","reputation":1808,"display_name":"Dexter"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":38850,"edited":false,"creation_date":1442514877,"comment_id":64759,"body":"Certainly not a dragonfly. This looks like a grasshopper but I can&#39;t tell the species."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0la1I.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4833,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4833/dexter","reputation":1808,"display_name":"Dexter"},"score":0,"post_id":3885