ng of the platform used. Also, do not forget that many sequencers need some bases (20-40) to warm up, and some other to land. E.G. I want to sequence a fragment from bp 100 to 150 of a given gene: I will design primers starting from bp 50-70 and stop at about 170. Personally I design primers pairs for any coding exon of a gene."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1447939454,"creation_date":1437542895,"body":"<p>I think various ways can be apply, but the easiest way could be to indicate the range to set a forward primer. <\/p>\n\n<p>Decide the length of primer you are going to get. <\/p>\n\n<p>Let's say you would like 25 mer. <\/p>\n\n<p>You can set the range from <strong>chr12:25398261<\/strong> to <strong>chr12:25398309<\/strong>. <\/p>\n\n<p>When you identify where <strong>chr12:25398285<\/strong> is in <strong>NG_007524.1<\/strong>, you are ready to design your primers.<\/p>\n","answer_id":36288,"question_id":36252,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1447939454}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/36252/primer-design-with-primer-blast-over-specific-site","last_activity_date":1455723306,"creation_date":1437426970,"answer_count":1,"title":"Primer Design with Primer-BLAST over specific site","body":"<p>I am trying to design primers using Primer-BLAST such that the forward primer spans a specific base pair site. <\/p>\n\n<p>I am looking at KRAS for which I believe the <strong>RefSeq ID<\/strong> is <strong>NG_007524.1<\/strong> and the forward primer should span <strong>chr12:25398285<\/strong>. <\/p>\n\n<p>However, I'm not sure how to restrict the design to accomplish this. Thanks.<\/p>\n","question_id":36252,"tags":["molecular-biology","bioinformatics","dna-sequencing","blast","primer"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":71,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1447939279},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/WWyWq.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17648,"link":"http://biology.stackexcha