an take place, which will eventually lead to the growth of the embryo tops and shoot. Furthermore, some seeds contain a hormone that inhibits germination and water is needed in order to wash it out of the seed. The water needed for these processes is absorbed by the micropyle. <\/li>\n<li><strong>Warmth<\/strong> \u2014  many of the metabolic events of germination use enzymes, and these are sensitive to temperatures. Temperature will often be used as a trigger for germination.<\/li>\n<li><strong>Oxygen<\/strong> \u2014 many of the metabolic events that occur during germination use energy. This energy is produced by aerobic respiration. <\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Many metabolic processes take place at the start of germination, such as the synthesis  of <em>giberrellin<\/em>, this is a plant hormone that stimulates mitosis and cell division in the embryo. Other plant hormones include <em>Abscisic acid (ABA)<\/em>, which regulates seed dormancy and germination. It has been found to stop germination once it has been placed in the soil, it causes the seed to enter a period of dormancy. This allows the seed to remain dormant until when the conditions are more favorable for the seed to grow. <\/p>\n","answer_id":43425,"question_id":43317,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43317/how-does-a-seed-determine-when-to-start-germination","last_activity_date":1455718671,"creation_date":1455462975,"answer_count":1,"title":"How does a seed determine when to start germination?","body":"<p>I'm sure there are many different ways for seeds of different species, but what is a general rule? Is it some kind of ideal temperature &amp; wetness that triggers a chemical reaction? What factors stimulate seeds to germinate?<\/p>\n","question_id":43317,"tags":["growth"],"score":6,"accepted_answer_id":43425,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":60,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1455718671},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/235adc3d41f8a86b01a5f37a03d76cc6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21933,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21933/user159527","reputation":21,"display_name":"user159527"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":43414,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455701131,"comment_id":75178,"body":"It is nice to see that MOBTC has included some stuff on systems biology. The edition that I read did not have these."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1455715091,"creation_date":1455699620,"body":"<p>For that you would need to understand the dynamical systems theory behind the loop. The point at which the oscillation starts is called the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hopf_bifurcation\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hopf-bifurcation<\/a>. I shall explain this in simple intuitive terms. Lets assume that Protein-<strong>X<\/strong> activates the production of Protein-<strong>Y<\/strong> which in-turn causes inhibition of Protein-<strong>X<\/strong> production. This is a negative feedback loop.<\/p>\n\n<p>X → Y <br>\nY ⊣ X<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Situation-1: No/little delay<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>You switch on the production of <strong>X<\/strong>. This leads to rapid production of <strong>Y<\/strong> which will in-turn quickly repress the formation of <strong>X<\/strong>. This would happen so quickly and all that would be observed is a reduction in the steady-state level of <strong>X<\/strong> (compared to an unregulated system). Mathematically, the eigenvalues of the system (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobian_matrix_and_determinant\" rel=\"nofollow\">jacobian<\/a> matrix- denotes the slope of the function) evaluated at the steady state would be negative and real.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Situation-2: Some delay<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>In this case, it will take some time for <strong>Y<\/strong> to accumulate. This will cause <strong>X<\/strong> to shoot up above its final steady state level. This, in-turn, will cause higher production of <strong>Y<\/strong>. Because of higher production of <strong>Y<\/strong>, <strong>X<\/strong> will start getting repressed strongly when <strong>Y<\/strong> gets accumulated and starts acting. This will cause <strong>X<\/strong> to shoot down below the steady-state but the magnitude of this shoot-\"down\", will be less than the first shoot-\"up\". Finally, the system will settle to the steady state. This phenomenon is called damped oscillation. In this case, the eigenvalues of the jacobian are complex with negative real parts.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Situation 3: long delay<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>In this case the delay between production of <strong>Y<\/strong> and its action is so high that the system does not damp but sustains its oscillations. The eigenvalues of the jacobian are imaginary. These kind of oscillations are generally sensitive to different factors. <\/p>\n\n<p>More robust forms of oscillations exist, called <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_cycle\" rel=\"nofollow\">limit cycles<\/a>. The network structures responsible for this are more complex than a delayed negative feedback loop. Typically it has a coupled positive and negative feedback. Understanding limit cycles is little bit more complicated and I shall not discuss them here. <\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>Also, check out these reviews:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Tyson, John J., and Béla Novák. \"<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1146/annurev.physchem.012809.103457\" rel=\"nofollow\">Functional motifs in biochemical reaction networks<\/a>.\" <em>Annual Review of Physical Chemistr<\/em>y 61 (2010): 219.<\/p>\n\n<p>Tyson, John J., Katherine C. Chen, and Béla Novák. \"<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0955-0674(03)00017-6\" rel=\"nofollow\">Sniffers, buzzers, toggles and blinkers: dynamics of regulatory and signaling pathways in the cell<\/a>.\" <em>Current Opinion in Cell Biology<\/em> 15.2 (2003): 221-231.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>and this book:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Alon, Uri. <em><a href=\"https://www.crcpress.com/An-Introduction-to-Systems-Biology-Design-Principles-of-Biological-Circuits/Alon/9781584886426\" rel=\"nofollow\">An introduction to systems biology: design principles of biological circuits<\/a><\/em>. CRC press, 2006. ISBN 9781584886426<\/p>\n","answer_id":43423,"question_id":43414,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1455715091}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43414/negative-feedback-loop-and-oscillations","last_activity_date":1455718607,"creation_date":1455659971,"answer_count":1,"title":"Negative feedback loop and oscillations","body":"<p>According to the textbook <a href=\"http://www.garlandscience.com/product/isbn/9780815341055\" rel=\"nofollow\">Alberts Molecular Biology of the Cell<\/a> (5th ed., p. 902), negative feedback loops cause oscillations when they are long delayed. I just can't figure out why. <\/p>\n\n<p>Except for that, in case of short delayed feedback, the inhibition doesn't seem to be full and to go down only mid-way, according to the attached plot. Why?<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Yezzp.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Yezzp.png\" alt=\"image attached\"><\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":43414,"tags":["molecular-biology","systems-biology"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":58,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1455718607},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1220249427989573/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":21691,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21691/jyothi-nagraj","reputation":21,"display_name":"Jyothi Nagraj"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43426/problem-with-phosphorylated-and-total-forms-of-antibodies","last_activity_date":1455715820,"creation_date":1455715820,"answer_count":0,"title":"Problem with phosphorylated and total forms of antibodies","body":"<p>Antibodies are available that can detect both phosphorylated and total endogeneous levels of the given protein. I have a question here, why is it necessary to have equal amounts of total protein? This is a common assumption that variations come in phosphorylation status but since total detects levels of both phosphorylated and non-phosphorylated forms, it is supposed to be equal. Not necessarily! Depending on the requirement of cells, phosphorylation status may change. And so does the expression of the total protein itself specially if the non-phosphorylated form is acting as a transcription factor.This is what I find in my studies as well. But the literature suggests the opposite. Why?<\/p>\n","question_id":43426,"tags":["molecular-biology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":17,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":2,"post_id":43424,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455700696,"comment_id":75177,"body":"You could also PCR amplify the gene using primers with fitting restriction enzyme recognition sites (+ some extra bases) on the ends."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":43424,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455705054,"comment_id":75184,"body":"PCR, as Chris suggested. Also, when you made the cDNA library, you don&#39;t really have &quot;whole DNA&quot; as you suggested, but many pieces of DNA corresponding to the mRNAs you extracted. Some of those should be the gene of interest and can be amplified."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"score":0,"post_id":43424,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455706037,"comment_id":75185,"body":"@user137 Thanks! Must one go through the mRNA &amp; cDNA  stages? Or is there an easier way to get the gene? e.g. Can&#39;t one extract the DNA itself from the plant cell nucleus. Why start from mRNA? Sorry if some of my questions are naive."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":43424,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455721821,"comment_id":75194,"body":"mRNAs are generally used because they tend to have a much higher copy number than genomic DNA and because the introns are already removed, so you are left with the coding sequence. You can isolate genomic DNA and do PCR directly off that, but the introns will be there, potentially making for a much much much larger gene. If you just want the exons, use the mRNA -&gt; cDNA approach. It should be pointed out that if you want to express protein in bacteria, the introns will probably not be removed properly on transcription, so the protein won&#39;t be right."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8adae36f7b1f7d9829a28a88ac38f826?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17239,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17239/curious-cat","reputation":212,"display_name":"curious_cat","accept_rate":30},"score":0,"post_id":43424,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455721912,"comment_id":75195,"body":"@user137 Makes a lot of sense now the way you described it! Thank you."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43424/how-to-cut-out-a-specific-named-gene-from-plant-dna","last_activity_date":1455699848,"creation_date":1455699848,"answer_count":0,"title":"How to cut out a specific named gene from plant DNA","body":"<p>Suppose one has extracted RNA from a plant, converted it to the corresponding cDNA &amp; amplified it but now wants to cut out a particular, already-sequenced gene out from it, how does one proceed?<\/p>\n\n<p>i.e. How does one cut out that particular segment of the whole DNA which one wants? Does one always find restriction sites (or rather cleavage sites)  at both ends of the desired gene segment &amp; then one treats the cDNA sample with those specific restriction enzymes? <\/p>\n\n<p>To get the gene s