gur.com/BXEu5.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/BXEu5.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>This cell line seems to be in culture since the 1940s, as the reference to Sanford, Earle and Likely, 1948 suggests. Digging up this reference (number 2 below) tells a bit more about the isolation:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The cells of this study were from Earle's strain\n  L (6), which originated from normal, subcutaneous,\n  connective tissue of an adult C311 strain\n  mouse.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Reference 6 in the Sanford et al. paper is:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>EARLE, W. R.: Production of malignancy in vitro.\n  IV. The mouse fibroblast cultures and changes\n  seen in the living cells. J. Nat. Cancer Inst, 4:\n  165-212 (1943).<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>which gives no further details. It is a methodic paper which analyzes the conditions necessary for cell culture - interesting on a historical point of view, since the techniques where developed at that time. The full PDF is linked in reference 3.<\/p>\n\n<p>About the name I need to speculate a bit, but since the original cells where named \"Strain L\", and LS cells where derived from there to grow in suspension, it might translate into Strain L Suspension cells.<\/p>\n\n<p>References:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"http://www1.zippyshare.com/v/2qt5re0c/file.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Uptake of Amino Acids by Mouse Cells (Strain LS) During Growth\nIn Batch Culture and Chemostat Culture: The Influence Of Cell Growth\nRate<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www94.zippyshare.com/v/6NV4Pait/file.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Growth in Vitro of Single Isolated Tissue Cells<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cuneyttas.com/EBSS-sol-J-of-National-Cancer-Institute-1943-Vol4-Iss2-pp165-212.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Production of Malignancy in Vitro.<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":43416,"question_id":43412,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43412/what-are-mouse-ls-cells","last_activity_date":1455661760,"creation_date":1455659325,"answer_count":1,"title":"What are mouse LS cells?","body":"<p>I have seen the term \"mouse LS cell\" used in several papers now, but I haven't found an explanation for the origin of these cells (for example, <a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Doug_Kilburn/publication/17407921_The_effect_of_dissolved_oxygen_partial_pressure_on_the_growth_and_metabolism_of_mouse_LS_cells/links/0fcfd506f59a6bc46c000000.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">this paper<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p>What are mouse LS cells? What is their origin (besides coming from mouse!)?<\/p>\n","question_id":43412,"tags":["cell-culture","mouse"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":43416,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":29,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-Q7qa9X6M8oE/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAACB4/NnR8G0JQGZc/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16041,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16041/solarlunix","reputation":1965,"display_name":"SolarLunix","accept_rate":100},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":2,"post_id":43415,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455674574,"comment_id":75161,"body":"It&#39;s TV mumbo jumbo (or justplain hyperbole). Pumps fueling jets pump at a rate of about 1,000 gallons per minute, and do so from the ground against gravity. The average heart pumps about 21 cups (1.3 gallons) per minute, and not very much against gravity. It <i>might<\/i> be strong enough to pump fuel to a jet, but depending on how high, it might be in milliliters per minute at best."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":1,"post_id":43415,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455681867,"comment_id":75165,"body":"A normal blood pressure is about 140 mm/Hg. Mercury has a density of 13.69 g/cm^3 while jet fuel is about 0.8  g/cm^3.  Applying a little math, we find that a heart should be able to pump jet fuel to about 2.4 meters, so maybe it could (slowly!) refuel a small bizjet, but not an airliner."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":43415,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455722932,"comment_id":75199,"body":"If you don&#39;t care about the rate, and put the heart at the same level as the engine, and don&#39;t mind that it won&#39;t pump very long without blood, oxygen, or food, then yes."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43415/could-a-human-heart-really-pump-fuel-up-to-a-jet-engine","last_activity_date":1455661532,"creation_date":1455661532,"answer_count":0,"title":"Could a human heart really pump fuel up to a jet engine?","body":"<p>In Parks and Recreation, Chris is told his heart was strong enough to \"pump fuel to a jet engine\". What I'm wondering is the following:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Does an extremely healthy human heart have the power to do this, or was it just the usual TV mambo jumbo?<\/li>\n<li>How can we measure the full pumping power of the heart? I.E. How do we know that a human heart is or isn't capable of pumping fuel to a jet engine?<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","question_id":43415,"tags":["human-biology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":51,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d4d0917cf3785fd7bc9e95abeb1bcd1d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1"