 model to measure the K and Na currents at rest (~$-65$ $mV$) and it showed that the K current is ~4 times stronger. I would caution that this is just a simple simulation however, but it predicts that the sodium channels don&#39;t fully close at rest state, and in fact allow small amounts of Na Ions to leak across the membrane.  Still looking at primary literature however, and not sure this level of detail is necessary to answer the question. Thus a comment."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":43379,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455608980,"comment_id":75064,"body":"Question is on resting membrane potential and K+ is the main player in this due to leakiness afaik."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61088ee58466316218f96ae12fb35c9a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13388,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13388/xelo747","reputation":463,"display_name":"xelo747"},"score":1,"post_id":43379,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455610867,"comment_id":75069,"body":"@Christiaan not sure what afaik is? At any rate, I looked more into it and I see your point, Ignoring the small contributions of sodium gives a good description. Furthermore, your answer in from (<a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/21394/what-keeps-the-resting-potential-of-neurons-constant-at-70-mv\" title=\"what keeps the resting potential of neurons constant at 70 mv\">biology.stackexchange.com/questions/21394/&hellip;<\/a>)  you are completely right the pump c