-phosphate (a triose) is the immediate product the cycle; 2 of these can be condensed to fructose-2,6-biphophate by aldolase, and from there on to other hexoses, like glucose."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"score":0,"post_id":43320,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455593844,"comment_id":75040,"body":"&quot;2 of these can be condensed to fructose-2,6-biphophate&quot; thats what I am asking. How and in which step (of so-called reverse glycolysis after calvin cycle) does it take place? BTW am I so bad in framing questions?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"score":0,"post_id":43320,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455596701,"comment_id":75043,"body":"Also, 3-PGAL is the immediate product of single cycle. So as per what you said, 2 cycles (2 CO2 fixed) should form 1 glucose(6C)?????"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":0,"post_id":43320,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455606763,"comment_id":75062,"body":"You were asking about the &quot;1/6 of glucose&quot; and how it derives from CO2; this is via glyceraldehyde-phosphate. No, I did not imply that 2 CO2 makes 1 glucose, that&#39;s obviously not correct; but 2 glyceraldehyde-phosphate makes 1 glucose. And for net production of 1 triose, 3 CO2 must be captured. I don&#39;t think it makes much sense to talk about &quot;turns&quot; of the cycle, I hear this often about metabolic cycles, but I think it&#39;s better to just look at the stoichiometry of the reactions. (It&#39;s not actually a wheel :)  I will extend the answer with the aldolase part."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"score":0,"post_id":43320,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455616390,"comment_id":75079,"body":"Though I have selected it, I would appreciate it if you add this in your answer: We know that the cycle is just a series of reactions occuring periodically (if this is correct word here). We also know that 1 RuBisCO cannot take on 6 reactions at a time, it does so one-by-one. So lets think that there are 6 CO2 fixation reactions going on. Now they form 12 (separate) 3-PGAL, 2 of which condense to form 1 glucose and other 10 (separate) 3-PGAL consense to form 6 (separate) RuBP."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1455607569,"creation_date":1455465292,"body":"<p>It's not really possible to break it down this way. The CO2 fixated by the RUBISCO enzyme generates two phosphoglycerate (2 x 3C) molecules from one ribulose bisphophate molecule (5C), while the rest of the Calvin cycle serves to regenerate 3 ribulose bisphophate from 5 phosphoglycerate. Hence, one 3-carbon sugar (glyceraldehyde phosphate or dihydroxyacetone phosphate) can exit the cycle for every 3 CO3 captured. The regeneration of ribulose bisphosphate involves several enzymes, and the stoichiometry is rather complicated; it would take an entire essay to describe it all. I suggest you look the <a href=\"http://metacyc.org/META/NEW-IMAGE?type=PATHWAY&amp;object=CALVIN-PWY&amp;detail-level=1\" rel=\"nofollow\">calvin cycle in the metacyc database<\/a>, it's a nice interactive resource where you can explore all the details of the reactions. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light-independent_reactions\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia<\/a> also provides some details on these reactions.<\/p>\n\n<p>The glyceraldehyde phosphate produced by the Calvin cycle is then converted to glucose and other sugars by the enzymes of gluconeogenesis. The key enzyme is <a href=\"http://metacyc.org/META/NEW-IMAGE?type=REACTION-IN-PATHWAY&amp;object=F16ALDOLASE-RXN\" rel=\"nofollow\">fructose diphosphate aldolase<\/a> (or simply \"aldolase\") which condenses glyceraldehyde phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate to one fructose-1,6-diphosphate. A chart of the pathway leading to other sugars is <a href=\"http://metacyc.org/META/NEW-IMAGE?type=PATHWAY&amp;object=SUCSYN-PWY\" rel=\"nofollow\">found here<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":43320,"question_id":43293,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1455607569}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43293/how-are-6-fixed-co2-molecules-joined-toegther-as-glucose","last_activity_date":1455607569,"creation_date":1455369175,"answer_count":1,"title":"How are 6 \"fixed\" CO2 molecules joined toegther as glucose?","body":"<p>When we study calvin cycle, we study it with 6 molecules so as to form 1 glucose in a single cycle as:<\/p>\n\n<p>6 RuBP + 6 CO2 => 12 3-PGAL => 1 Glucose + 6 RuMP<\/p>\n\n<p>But if we look deep, then we know that the molecules are synthesized one-by-one &amp; 6 cycles give 1 glucose, but:<\/p>\n\n<p>1 RuBP + 1 CO2 => ... => 1/6 Glucose + 1 RuMP<\/p>\n\n<p>My question: <strong>What is actually this 1/6 glucose (organic carbon fixed from inorganic carbon and how are such 6 molecules joined together?<\/strong><\/p>\n","question_id":43293,"tags":["biochemistry","photosynthesis","glucose"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":43320,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":69,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1455383261},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/166093d036b7185b3a53052889d99e47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1472,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1472/mew","reputation":836,"display_name":"Mew","accept_rate":86},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":5693,"edited":false,"creation_date":1357550575,"comment_id":8177,"body":"I&#39;ve put the evolution tag on this because I feel it is an evolutionary question... &quot;Why did eggs evolve to be egg shaped?&quot;"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":8,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/166093d036b7185b3a53052889d99e47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1472,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1472/mew","reputation":836,"display_name":"Mew","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":5694,"edited":false,"creation_date":1357567566,"comment_id":8183,"body":"Thanks rg255.  Shortly after posting up my question I found that site also and found it very interesting."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1357549734,"creation_date":1357546031,"body":"<p>There is variance in egg shape; sea-birds often use a more pear or conical shaped egg to prevent it from rolling off the cliff (where they nest) if it is disturbed. Some reptiles lay very spherical eggs (some turtles) whereas some reptiles lay very elongated ones (see black pine snake eggs). <\/p>\n\n<p>I imagine that we don't see square eggs because they would be difficult to shape and difficult to lay. Shape may also influence strength. <\/p>\n\n<p>Google your question (like I did after writing the above) and it will come up with <a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2012/05/01/3492086.htm\">this article<\/a> which pretty much says what I just did. Here are some of the author's key points...<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"If eggs were rectangular little boxes, they would be very strong on the corners, but very weak in the middle of the straight walls.\"<\/p>\n  \n  <p>\"The strongest shape of all is a ball, or sphere. But if you were to push or gently nudge a spherical egg, it would roll away downhill, never to be seen again.\"<\/p>\n  \n  <p>\"So one reason that eggs have an asymmetric tapered oval shape is that if you nudge them, they'll come back to you. They'll sweep out a circle around the pointed end, and come to a stop with the pointed end facing uphill. In fact, the eggs of birds that have their nests on cliffs are more oval than the eggs of birds that nest on the ground. This means the 'more-oval' eggs of these cliff-nesting birds will roll in a very tight little circle, and be less likely to roll out of the nest \u2014 and off the cliff.\"<\/p>\n  \n  <p>\"Another reason for eggs to be egg-shaped is that they fit together quite snugly in the nest, with only small air spaces between them. \"<\/p>\n  \n  <p>\"Yet another reason that eggs are tapered is so that they can get pushed out of the hen.\"<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":5694,"question_id":5693,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1357549734}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/5693/why-are-eggs-egg-shaped","last_activity_date":1455606644,"creation_date":1357539856,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why are eggs \"egg\" shaped?","body":"<p>Is there a reason as to why chickens lay \"egg\" shaped eggs, as opposed to spherically shaped eggs (or a random shape)?  &lt;--- Main Question<\/p>\n\n<p>For extra points (actually just to add more words in order to meet the \"quality\" standards of the site):<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>why do plant seeds often come in this same \"egg\" shape (e.g. avocado\n  seeds), as opposed to a sphere?  Is it a coincidence that avocado\n  seeds and eggs are the same shape?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","question_id":5693,"tags":["evolution","embryology"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":5694,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":602,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1357550586},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d73b744d13b037aa03db3eed410c301a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21686,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21686/john","reputation":33,"display_name":"John"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TSuGp.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19521,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19521/jordi-zambrino","reputation":1024,"display_name":"Jordi Zambrino","accept_rate":83},"score":1,"post_id":43357,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455565521,"comment_id":75009,"body":"People with anorexia usually tend to have high levels of cortisol, the brain hormone most related to stress, and decreased levels of serotonin and norepinephrine, which are associated with feelings of well-being. But you may want to ask this question on the <i>Cognitive Sciences Stack exchange<\/i>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":43357,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TSuGp.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19521,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19521/jordi-zambrino","reputation":1024