8&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455586484,"comment_id":75033,"body":"@James How would the Gram negative bacteria (or any bacteria) be endocytosed or enter the cytoplasm of the proto-eukaryotic cell if it&#39;s not surrounded by a vesicle?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":43372,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455587854,"comment_id":75034,"body":"From the link you shared &quot;It&#39;s simply not true that the double membranes of bacteria and chloroplasts were the result of endocytosis.&quot; After a brief bit of googling and reading some comments by internet folk I am convinced that the third membrane could be lost. I still can&#39;t answer the question though. Very interesting!"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43372/origin-of-the-double-membrane-of-mitochondria-and-chloroplasts","last_activity_date":1455585625,"creation_date":1455585625,"answer_count":0,"title":"Origin of the double membrane of mitochondria and chloroplasts","body":"<p>Most websites and textbooks say that the double membrane of mitochondria and chloroplasts are a result of the endocytosis of ancient prokaryotes (the outer membrane is from the vesicle containing the prokaryote, the inner membrane is from the prokaryote itself).\nHowever, some sources say that this is not the case. The precursor to the mitochondrion (alphaproteobacteria) was a gram-negative bacteria, which has a double membrane. <a href=\"http://sandwalk.blogspot.com/2010/06/on-origin-of-double-membrane-in.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">This site<\/a> says that the reasoning for the double membrane that is often taught is a lie, and that the mitochondrial precursor had a double membrane already to generate ATP through the ETC.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, if this is the case, why do mitochondria now have two membranes, and not three (two from the prokaryote and one from the vesicle)?<\/p>\n","question_id":43372,"tags":["mitochondria","chloroplasts"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":43,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2cf2eee5993f6cf3b0b149c2f8c5a323?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"moderator","user_id":63,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/63/robert-cartaino","reputation":101,"display_name":"Robert Cartaino"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":0,"post_id":43371,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455583997,"comment_id":75030,"body":"<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12790671\" rel=\"nofollow\">ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12790671<\/a> is this essentially what you&#39;re looking for?"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43371/how-to-promote-denitrifying-microbe-activity","last_activity_date":1455584142,"creation_date":1455582664,"answer_count":0,"title":"How to promote denitrifying microbe activity","body":"<p>I'm an amateur fresh-water aquarist looking at the problem of <em>nitrate<\/em> reduction (into  largely-inert nitrogen gas) in a small-scale aquarium environment. The process of turning the byproducts of fish waste and respiration into ammonium (NH<sub>4<\/sub><sup>+<\/sup>) &rarr; nitrite (NO<sub>2<\/sub><sup>−<\/sup>) &rarr; nitrate (NO<sub>3<\/sub><sup>−<\/sup>) is relatively simple because the nitrifying bacteria can easily thrive in the aerobic environment of the filter and home aquarium. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>But the <em>denitrification<\/em> of nitrates (NO<sub>3<\/sub><sup>−<\/sup>) into molecular nitrogen (N<sub>2<\/sub>) isn't so easy.<\/strong> The problem seems to be that you don't have enough <em>anaerobic<\/em> activity in a living aquarium environment to promote denitrofying microbes to any great degree. <\/p>\n\n<p>So hypothetically&hellip;<\/p>\n\n<p>If I were to <em>remove<\/em> the water and transfer it into another environment (one where I didn't need to support fish), <strong>what environmental conditions would I need to kick this <em>anaerobic<\/em> activity into overdrive?<\/strong> <\/p>\n\n<p>I've been reading about using autotrophs (plants and algae) to reduce nitrates, but I'm particularly interested using anaerobic bacteria in anaerobic conditions to promote denitrification. <\/p>\n","question_id":43371,"tags":["biochemistry","microbiology","bacteriology","environment"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":17,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1455584142},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4b6eac368964ea096f57cb1dbb989a20?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13417,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13417/edward","reputation":136,"display_name":"Edward"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":0,"post_id":43324,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455580395,"comment_id":75026,"body":"A cytokine antibody array followed by IL-6 ELISA to validate the results is at least one method I can think of. BioRad has a lot of kits for quantifying cytokines, I&#39;ve never used it but I&#39;ve seen a few papers use their <a href=\"http://www.bio-rad.com/en-us/product/bio-plex-precision-pro-human-cytokine-assays\" rel=\"