nce fragment.  ELISA tests and protein assays exist in medical diagnostics, usually detecting antibodies for the reason that you state: pathogens are often not found in the blood.  It is also worth pointing out that screening procedures for rare pathogens is almost certainly going to result in many false positives.  If only 1 in 1000 people with generic symptoms actually have pathogen A, but the test has a 1% false positive rate, then only about 1 in 10 people who test positive on the test will actually have the disease."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b0c3f6f5094c2a15cb153a243a80de75?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21844,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21844/gyro-gearloose","reputation":148,"display_name":"Gyro Gearloose"},"score":0,"post_id":43358,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ab9ee46f264268ae3e1389224e16d1e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19203,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19203/hans","reputation":417,"display_name":"Hans"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455570372,"comment_id":75022,"body":"@Hans If the initial test is really cheap and significant enough over a random coin, the second drop of blood could be analyzed by a more specific (and in need, more expensive) test. If not better in the way of finding the cause, it would at least be cheaper then that those doctors of mine charged me."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43358/cheap-effective-searching-for-pathogenes","last_activity_date":1455564804,"creation_date":1455564804,"answer_count":0,"title":"Cheap, effective searching for pathogenes?","body":"<p>Background: some time ago, I suffered from some recurrent sickness, with frequency of about 2 weeks. As far as I learned, this is a sure sign of an infection. I've been to the doctors, and they did work a lot (at least, they charged me worth more than 1000$). For all this effort and 