ound the world.<\/p>\n\n<p>Going back to plain vanilla geography, most islands in the Pacific Ocean can be grouped into one of three regions - Melanesia, Micronesia and Polynesia. The most notable group of islands in the Atlantic are the islands of the Caribbean, which are part of the New World. Biogeographers classify the Caribbean (along with the southern tip of Florida) as part of the Neotropic ecozone.<\/p>\n","answer_id":42346,"question_id":42330,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":1,"post_id":43326,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455499768,"comment_id":74957,"body":"One problem is that taxonomic nomenclature is constantly changing. So we might refer to New World monkeys as &quot;Cebidae&quot; one year and something else another year. In that spirit, terms like &quot;New World monkeys&quot; are very useful. It&#39;s also very common for biologists to compare Old World and New World groups (e.g. New World cervids vs Old World cervids). Sometimes they compare Old World-New World-Australasian groups - like moles, golden moles and Australian marsupial moles."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":43326,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6